{
  "texts": [
    "(80)Also for standard SK with J ij ∼ N (0, 1), which is a special case of µ(N) = 0, it is known thatlim N →∞ E J [max z G(z)] N 3/2 = Π *, (81)where Π * is the Parisi value [49].",
    "Thus for J ij ∼ N (0, σ 2), it is easily seen thatlim N →∞ E J [max z G(z)] N 3/2 = σΠ *.",
    "(82)To summarize, the limiting behavior for SK with a distribution with any σ ̸ = 1 can be obtained by simple rescaling.",
    "To connect this to the quantities discussed at the end of Section 4.3, for N (0, σ 2), the quantity V p in Equation (71) scales asV p (γ, β) = V p,1 (γ, β) = V p,σ ( γ σ, β).Therefore for the remainder of this Section we focus on the case where µ(N) ̸ = 0.If µ(N) → µ as N → ∞ for some nonzero constant µ, the term involving µ(N) dominates, and the expected maximum is Θ(N 2).",
    "More specifically, using the definition of h(N) in (75) for nonzero µ, we get that lim N →∞ µ(N)h(N) = Θ(N 2), and both sides of Equation (79) are of the same order in N. Thus the squeeze theorem implies that the limiting quantity is exactlylim N →∞ E J [max z G(z)] N 2 = µ 2(1 + sign(µ)), (83)where we define sign(x) to be 1 when x ≥ 0 and 0 when x < 0."
  ]
}